import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Create bins for the charges
bins = np.linspace(min(data_cleaned['charges']), max(data_cleaned['charges']), 30)  # Adjust the number of bins as needed

# Create a histogram using the bins to calculate frequency
frequency, bin_edges = np.histogram(data_cleaned['charges'], bins=bins)

# Calculate the center of each bin for plotting
bin_centers = 0.5 * (bin_edges[1:] + bin_edges[:-1])

# Create a line plot for charges vs frequency (using bins)
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(bin_centers, frequency, color="red")
plt.title('Line Graph of Charges vs Frequency (Binned)')
plt.xlabel('Charges')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')

# Display the line graph
plt.show()

# Define the conditions for the 'status' column
conditions = [
    (data_cleaned['sex'] == 'female') & (data_cleaned['children'] > 0),
    (data_cleaned['sex'] == 'male') & (data_cleaned['children'] > 0),
    (data_cleaned['children'] == 0)
]

# Define the corresponding values for the conditions
values = ['Parent', 'Parent', 'Single']

# Add a default value to avoid dtype conflicts
data_cleaned['status'] = np.select(conditions, values, default='Unknown')

# Display the first few rows
print(data_cleaned[['sex', 'children', 'status']].head())

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# List of all columns except 'charges' (target variable)
features = [col for col in data_cleaned.columns if col != 'charges']

# Calculate the number of rows and columns for the subplots grid
num_features = len(features)
cols = 3  # Number of columns in the subplot grid
rows = (num_features + cols - 1) // cols  # Calculate required rows

# Create a subplot grid
fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, cols, figsize=(15, 5 * rows))
fig.tight_layout(pad=5.0)

# Flatten the axes array for easier iteration
axes = axes.flatten()

# Loop through each feature and create a scatter plot
for i, feature in enumerate(features):
    sns.scatterplot(x=feature, y='charges', data=data_cleaned, ax=axes[i])
    axes[i].set_title(f'{feature} vs Charges')
    axes[i].set_xlabel(feature)
    axes[i].set_ylabel('Charges')

# Remove any empty subplots (if number of features < total subplots)
for i in range(len(features), len(axes)):
    fig.delaxes(axes[i])

# Show the plots
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score

# Calculate Q1 and Q3 for 'age'
Q1 = data_cleaned['age'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = data_cleaned['age'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

# Determine the bounds for outliers
lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

# Filter the data to remove outliers
data_filtered = data_cleaned[(data_cleaned['age'] >= lower_bound) & (data_cleaned['age'] <= upper_bound)]

# Select 'age' as the feature and 'charges' as the target without outliers
X = data_filtered[['age']]  # Feature (independent variable)
y = data_filtered['charges']  # Target (dependent variable)


# # Select 'age' as the feature and 'charges' as the target with outliers
# X = data_cleaned[['age']]  # Feature (independent variable)
# y = data_cleaned['charges']  # Target (dependent variable)

# Split the data into training and testing sets (70% training, 30% testing)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Initialize the Linear Regression model
lr = LinearRegression()

# Train the model on the training data
lr.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on the test data
y_pred = lr.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the model
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
coefficients = lr.coef_  # Returns an array of coefficients
intercept = lr.intercept_  # Returns the intercept


print(f"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mse}")
print(f"R-squared: {r2}")
print(f"y-intercept(b value): {intercept}")
print(f"Coefficient (weight): {coefficients}")

# Visualize the regression line and the data
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

# Scatter plot of age vs charges (Test data)
plt.scatter(X_test, y_test, color='blue', label='Actual Data')

# Plot the regression line
plt.plot(X_test, y_pred, color='red', linewidth=2, label='Regression Line')

plt.title('Linear Regression: Age vs Charges')
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Charges')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score

# Filter the data to remove rows where 'charges' exceed 15000
data_filtered = data_cleaned[data_cleaned['charges'] <= 15000]

# Additional filter: Remove rows where charges > 10000 for age < 50
data_filtered = data_filtered[~((data_filtered['age'] < 50) & (data_filtered['charges'] > 10000))]

# Select 'age' as the feature and 'charges' as the target with the new filter
X = data_filtered[['age']]  # Feature (independent variable)
y = data_filtered['charges']  # Target (dependent variable)

# Split the data into training and testing sets (70% training, 30% testing)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Initialize the Linear Regression model
lr = LinearRegression()

# Train the model on the training data
lr.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on the test data
y_pred = lr.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the model
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
coefficients = lr.coef_  # Returns an array of coefficients
intercept = lr.intercept_  # Returns the intercept

# Print results
print(f"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mse}")
print(f"R-squared: {r2}")
print(f"y-intercept (b value): {intercept}")
print(f"Coefficient (weight): {coefficients}")

# Visualize the regression line and the data
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

# Scatter plot of age vs charges (Test data)
plt.scatter(X_test, y_test, color='blue', label='Actual Data')

# Plot the regression line
plt.plot(X_test, y_pred, color='red', linewidth=2, label='Regression Line')

plt.title('Linear Regression: Age vs Charges (Filtered Data)')
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Charges')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score, mean_absolute_error

# Assuming data_cleaned is your DataFrame and charges is the target variable
X = data_cleaned.drop(columns=['charges'])  # Features
y = data_cleaned['charges']  # Target

# Split the dataset
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Initialize and train the Random Forest Regressor
rf = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions
y_pred = rf.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the model
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)

# Print the evaluation metrics
print(f"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mse:.2f}")
print(f"Mean Absolute Error (MAE): {mae:.2f}")
print(f"R-squared: {r2:.2f}")

# Visualization: Scatter plot of predicted vs actual charges
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(y_test, y_pred, color='blue', alpha=0.5, label='Predicted Charges')
plt.plot([y.min(), y.max()], [y.min(), y.max()], color='red', linestyle='--', label='Ideal Prediction')  # Ideal line
plt.title('Random Forest Regressor: Predicted vs Actual Charges')
plt.xlabel('Actual Charges')
plt.ylabel('Predicted Charges')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error, r2_score

# Define a grid of parameters around the best parameters found using Randomized Search
param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [250, 280, 284, 300],  # Narrowing around the found n_estimators
    'max_depth': [None, 5, 6, 7],  # Include found value and test nearby values
    'min_samples_split': [5, 6, 7, 8],  # Include found value and nearby values
    'min_samples_leaf': [4, 5, 6],  # Include found value and nearby values
    'max_features': [None, 'sqrt', 'log2']  # Include None and other common options
}

# Initialize the Random Forest Regressor
rf = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=42)

# Initialize GridSearchCV
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=rf, param_grid=param_grid, cv=5, n_jobs=-1, verbose=2)

# Fit the model
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Print the best parameters and best score
print("Best parameters found: ", grid_search.best_params_)
print("Best cross-validated score: ", grid_search.best_score_)

# Use the best estimator from grid search to make predictions
best_rf = grid_search.best_estimator_
y_pred = best_rf.predict(X_test)

# Calculate performance metrics
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)

# Print the metrics
print(f"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mse:.2f}")
print(f"Mean Absolute Error (MAE): {mae:.2f}")
print(f"R-squared: {r2:.2f}")

# Visualization: Scatter plot of predicted vs actual charges
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(y_test, y_pred, color='blue', alpha=0.5, label='Predicted Charges')

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error, r2_score
from scipy.stats import randint, uniform

# Define the parameter distribution
param_dist = {
    'n_estimators': randint(100, 500),  # Sample from 100 to 500
    'max_depth': [None] + list(range(5, 31, 5)),  # Sample None and depths from 5 to 30
    'min_samples_split': randint(2, 15),  # Sample from 2 to 15
    'min_samples_leaf': randint(1, 6),  # Sample from 1 to 6
    'max_features': ['sqrt', 'log2', None]  # Consider None, sqrt, and log2 as options
}

# Initialize the Random Forest Regressor
rf = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=42)

# Initialize RandomizedSearchCV
random_search = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=rf, param_distributions=param_dist,
                                   n_iter=100, cv=5, n_jobs=-1, random_state=42, verbose=2)

# Fit the model
random_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Print the best parameters and best score
print("Best parameters found: ", random_search.best_params_)
print("Best cross-validated score: ", random_search.best_score_)

# Use the best estimator from random search to make predictions
best_rf = random_search.best_estimator_
y_pred = best_rf.predict(X_test)

# Calculate performance metrics
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)

# Print the metrics
print(f"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mse:.2f}")
print(f"Mean Absolute Error (MAE): {mae:.2f}")
print(f"R-squared: {r2:.2f}")

# Visualization: Scatter plot of predicted vs actual charges
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(y_test, y_pred, color='blue', alpha=0.5, label='Predicted Charges')
